english:
  title: Record of the Hall of Two Delights
  author: Kim Il-son
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Traveling eastward from the Central Plains toward Jukryeong, the landscape unfolds with countless wonders. Beyond the stations of Hwanggang and Susan, traversing all of Cheongpung's realm and crossing a mountain pass into Danyang's borders, we arrive at Janghoewon Temple. There, drawing rein below its walls, we gradually enter a realm of extraordinary beauty.

    Suddenly, towering rocks thrust upward, peaks cluster in verdant layers, while mist confounds left and right, east and west—a spectacle no master of meteorology could untangle. As chasms split and cliffs part asunder, a single river pours through the center, its waters shimmering in lapis and jade. Along the northern shore, hundreds of steps up a perilous slope, stands a citadel fit for concealment—anciently known as Hidden Cliff. There I paused my horse and gazed into swirling mists, seized by fancies of that immortal axeman whose handle turned to dust. Grieving that such a masterpiece bore no name, I christened it the Cinnabar Valley.

    Beyond the valley, eastward the mountains grew stranger still, the waters ever more crystalline. After ten li the gorge concluded—like parting from a beloved, I turned back nine times in ten steps. Ahead, Scarlet City rose within arm's reach, and by the river's edge a crossing appeared. A small boat ferried us across to the Lower Ford. Ascending the waters some ten li further, we found the Official Crossing—the Upper Ford—where iron walls a thousand fathoms high loom above the current, their majesty striking such awe into the soul that none may scale them. Thus I named it the Falcon's Roost.

    The source of this Upper Ford flows from Mount Odae in Gangneung Prefecture, winding through valleys for five or six hundred li, its waters too vast for even the lightest boat to fully trace. Returning with the current, before reaching the Lower Ford again, a spring arrives from the south—anciently called the Southern Stream. Upon its left bank stands a pavilion, wing-like and graceful. As darkness fell, we could not ascend, so we lodged at the county quarters.

    The next dawn, County Magistrate Hwang Inryun invited us to climb. Together we grasped the railings and gazed outward. Swallows darted through air, roosters pecked at insects, magpies called—guests arrived. Clouds draped the mountain's crown, autumn light spilled like silk and brocade. Layered peaks, ridge upon ridge, embraced the pavilion entire, while the Southern Stream's waters sang beneath the railings and the Upper Ford's waves gathered in the forest's depths. All that yesterday's saddle and boat had shown us now lay spread before our wine cups and tables. Truly, what two eyes beheld exceeded what two legs had traveled.

    On the wall hung three great characters written by one surnamed Bi: "Hall of Two Delights"—radiant as moonlight on a luminous night, their brilliance beyond grasping. Streams and mountains held their glow. I could not contain my joy and said to Magistrate Hwang: "Only the benevolent truly delight in mountains; only the wise truly delight in waters. One who does not err for three months nears benevolence; what can be known across a hundred generations approaches wisdom. Yet should one lacking this still chase feeling through landscapes, is this not deceiving oneself?

    "All possess benevolence and wisdom by nature, yet few cultivate their roots. To cultivate them requires no gift beyond one's station. Embodying the mountain's stillness that does not wander, the water's motion without stagnation, settling the heart's virtue and encompassing all things' transformations—then the true joy of these two delights becomes one's own.

    "The Magistrate, possessed of tranquil character and understanding of principle, finds it easy to serve his parents and through filial teaching governs a whole domain. He employs few people justly, levies taxes on poor soil equitably, manages all fitly, fulfills his records and contributions—yet still reserves strength for pavilions, restoring their decay while preserving their ancient form. Thus his benevolence and wisdom shine clear. Should he advance from this, his learning reaching principle's ultimate flow, his action becoming effortless, then high mountains and flowing waters become the very body of his benevolence and wisdom.

    "But should one merely raise a cup, grow drunk on music, and find delight only in viewing what stands silent as stone and flows soundless as mist, rejoicing merely in their beauty and clarity, then one risks becoming like those who wear wooden clogs to exhaust the mountains or cast away gold to abandon duty—bringing shame upon the meaning of these two delights.

    "Let all of us who have climbed today encourage one another, and encourage all those who climb hereafter without end."

    Who were those who climbed with us? Gwon Gyeong-yeo of Hwasan, Kim Se-yeong of Saryeol, along with the Magistrate's brothers Wi and Pil—all students of Confucius. Thus we encouraged one another and passed this encouragement to all who would come after, world without end.
  footnotes:
    - The 'axeman' reference alludes to a famous Chinese legend of a woodcutter who, stopping to watch immortals play chess, found centuries had passed and his axe handle had turned to dust.
    - The 'Three Months' and 'Hundred Generations' reference Confucian ideals of moral cultivation and lasting virtue.
    - Hwasan (化山) and Saryeol (沙熱) are place names associated with the companions.
    - The final phrase 'without end' (於無窮云) suggests an infinite chain of moral cultivation passed from one generation to the next.
